WHITE WINES DATA ANALYSIS TRAINING¶

Celia Parejo Aranda (May-2019)

Dataset taken from: P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553, 2009.

Information from the authors: red and white wines datasets can be viewed as classification or regression tasks. The classes are ordered and not balanced (e.g. there are many more normal wines than excellent or poor ones). Outlier detection algorithms could be used to detect the few excellent or poor wines. Also, we are not sure if all input variables are relevant. So it could be interesting to test feature selection methods.

Variables:

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol
  • Quality (score between 0 and 10) (based on sensory data)

This graph clearly shows a relationship between quality and the 'alcohol' variable. It can be interesting to perform an ANOVA to check if the mean of alcohol content of the 'Medium' and 'High' quality wines are indeed higher than the low quality ones':

In [14]:
from scipy import stats
f_val, p_val = stats.f_oneway(wines[wines['alcohol_binned'] == 'Low']['quality'],
                              wines[wines['alcohol_binned'] == 'Medium']['quality'], 
                              wines[wines['alcohol_binned'] == 'High']['quality'])  

print( "ANOVA results: F=", f_val, ", P =", p_val)

ANOVA results: F= 501.21367251791844 , P = 9.39749934976259e-199

Yes. We can state, with a 95% confidence level, that wines with low alcohol content get statistically significant lower marks than those with 'Medium' or 'High' levels of alcohol.

Let's now dive into sulfur content.

But before that, we should know a bit about the role of sulfur in wines:

  • Sulfur dioxide exists as both free sulfur dioxide and bound sulfur dioxide in wine. Winemakers use the term total sulfur dioxide when referring to the sum of both the free and bound sulfur dioxide in wine. When sulfur dioxide (sulfites) is added to young wines, about half of the added sulfur dioxide quickly combines with other wine materials, and part of the sulfur dioxide added to wine remains in the free form (free sulfur dioxide). But, when sulfur dioxide is added to mature wines that contain relatively large amounts of sulfur dioxide, very little of the added sulfur dioxide becomes bound.
  • Free sulfur dioxide exists as molecular SO2, bisulfite and sulfite, and wine pH determines how free sulfur dioxide is distributed between these three forms.
  • This free sulfur dioxide, an in particular, molecular SO2, protects wine against microbes and oxidation. The unpleasant burnt match odor (noticeable sulfur smell) sometimes detected in wine depends primarily on the amount of SO2 present, rather than on the amount of free sulfur dioxide, and this depends on pH.
  • Large amounts of total sulfur dioxide in a wine may indicate excessive microbial activity, excessive wine oxidation, or poor storage conditions.
  • Most commercial wineries measure the free SO2 content of their wines every few weeks and additional sulfur dioxide is added as needed to maintain the molecular SO2 level at about 0.8 milligrams per liter (between 0.5 and 0.8).

Source: http://www.gencowinemakers.com/docs/Sulfur%20Dioxide.pdf

According to our results, we cannot define a specific relationship between pH and quality. Besides, as we already know, the great majority of the samples have a mark of 6, which makes it difficult to compare groups.

Let's continue with acidity.

Quick note about citric acid's origin in wines: according to the internet, 'While citric acid is very common in citrus fruits, (...) it is found only in very minute quantities in wine grapes (...). The citric acid most commonly found in wine is commercially produced acid supplements derived from fermenting sucrose solutions (...). Often to increase acidity of wine, winemakers will add tartaric acid instead'.

Knowing this, logic makes me think that the higher amount of citric acid, the lower the quality must be, as citric acid is nothing but a way to 'correct' acidity, which means that something went wrong during the fermentation period for whatever reason.

Let's check that:

Finally, let's go with chlorides and sulfates.

  • Calcium sulfate is used as a water hardening treatment. Having proper water hardness helps to increase the amount of sugars extracted and promotes the precipitation of haze causing proteins during fermentation. https://eckraus.com/calcium-sulfate-gypsum-purified/
  • Chlorides are a way of measuring the amount of salt in the wine. The level of chloride and sodium ions in wines essentially depends on the geographic, geologic and climatic conditions of vine culture. http://www.oiv.int/public/medias/2604/oiv-ma-d1-03.pdf
In [36]:

We could say that better wines tend to have lower amounts of chlorides, but there is such a high quantity of outliers that it is difficult to tell, added to the fact that we have very few wines with marks of 7, 8 or 9.

Here we have finished comparing single variables vs our target variable (quality). What if we try to combine two variables to see if, together, they show some kind of correlation with the marks?

We will try to do this with a few of them: alcohol, fixed acidity, free sulfur dioxide, density and pH, in the following combinations:

  • Alcohol and fixed acidity
  • Alcohol and free sulfur dioxide
  • Alcohol and pH
  • Density and pH

We already grouped 'alcohol' and 'free sulfur dioxide'. Let's bin the remaining variables:

from sklearn.feature_selection import VarianceThreshold
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn import metrics

def thresh_model(x_feat, y_feat, thresh):
    c = 1
    for i in thresh:
        var_th = VarianceThreshold(threshold = i)
        sel_var = var_th.fit_transform(x_feat)
        sel_var = x_feat.columns[var_th.get_support(indices=True)]
        print('Model', c, 'selected variables:', sel_var)
        
        c += 1
            
        wines_sel = wines.drop(sel_var, axis = 1)
        
        X = wines_sel.drop('quality',axis = 1)
        y = pd.DataFrame(wines_sel['quality'])
        
        scaler_X = StandardScaler().fit(X)
        scaled_X = scaler_X.transform(X)
        scaler_y = StandardScaler().fit(y)
        scaled_y = scaler_y.transform(y)
        
        X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(scaled_X, 
                                                            scaled_y, 
                                                            test_size = 0.3, 
                                                            random_state = 101)
       
        lm = LinearRegression()
        lm.fit(X_train, y_train)
        
        predictions = lm.predict(X_test)
        R2 = metrics.explained_variance_score(y_test, predictions)
        
        print(f'R2 for model {c} ({i}): {round(R2, 4)}')

With the given threshold values, the resulting combinations of features are all the same: 'fixed acidity', 'residual sugar', 'free sulfur dioxide', 'total sulfur dioxide' and 'alcohol', which, hence, are the ones with enough variability to explain at least part of the variation in the dependent variable.

Let's take a different approach for this variable selection to see if we obtain the same results. In this case, we will make use of the VIF value in order to eliminate those features that may cause collinearity:

In [49]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

def calculateVIF(data):
    features = list(data.columns)
    num_features = len(features)
    
    model = LinearRegression()
    
    result = pd.DataFrame(index = ['VIF'], columns = features)
    result = result.fillna(0)
    
    for i in range(num_features):
        x_feat = features[:]
        y_feat = features[i]
        x_feat.remove(y_feat)
        
        x = data[x_feat]
        y = data[y_feat]
    
        model.fit(data[x_feat], data[y_feat])
    
        result[y_feat] = 1/(1 - model.score(data[x_feat],data[y_feat]))
    
    return result
In [50]:
def selectDataByVIF(data, max_VIF = 5):
    result = data.copy(deep = True)
    
    VIF = calculateVIF(result)
    
    while VIF.values.max() > max_VIF:
        col_max = np.where(VIF == VIF.values.max())[1][0]
        features = list(result.columns)
        features.remove(features[col_max])
        result = result[features]
        
        VIF = calculateVIF(result)
    
    return result

Data modeling¶

The following step we are going to take will consist of trying to model the behaviour of 'quality' according to our selected features. We will first try with linear LASSO regression, different polynomial models, and random forest regressor to see if we can train a model which is able to predict marks.

Due to the inequal distribution of data among quality marks (there are many more 'good' wines than bad or excellent ones), and because of the presence of outliers, I honestly do not expect these models to be really precise. Nevertheless, all this exercise is for learning purposes. It is for that reason that we will later also try to implement a classification algorithm (Random Forest), for which the goal will be predicting if a wine is acceptable (quality of 6-9) or very poor (3-5).

In [66]:
def rfr_model(X, y):
    
    # Grid-Search
    gsc = GridSearchCV(
        estimator = RandomForestRegressor(),
        param_grid = {'max_depth': range(3,7),
                      'n_estimators': (10, 50, 100, 1000)}, cv = 5, 
        scoring  = 'neg_mean_squared_error', verbose = 0, n_jobs = -1)
    
    grid_result = gsc.fit(X, y)
    best_params = grid_result.best_params_

    rfr = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth = best_params['max_depth'], 
                                n_estimators = best_params['n_estimators'],
                                random_state = False, verbose = False)
    # K-Fold CV
    scores = cross_val_score(rfr, X, y, cv = 10, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error')
    return scores, best_params
